        <comment>
  <id>13788188</id>
  <body><![CDATA[The spare prose mimics Vermeer's careful use of light and shadow. I found the story to be what I consider historically accurate, especially in the description of the daily activities (and frustrations) of the Vermeer household. Theirs was a rigidly controlled society back then, where words were weapons and reputations, like virginity, could be lost forever in a moment. If the eighteen-year-old narrator spent a moment thinking over the implications of what the butcher just said, her reflection would not be inconsistent with a girl of her day... and the author's inclusion of that scene adds to the realism of the overall book. Your disappointment with this book indicates to me that you expected a modern novel, written in a modern style, instead of a novel based in the late 1600's and written with the (artfully imagined) voices and mannerisms of that period. Clearly, you will need to avoid Chevalier's other works, as they are also period pieces (which I have enjoyed tremendously). ]]></body>
  
