        <comment>
  <id>95783252</id>
  <body><![CDATA[The "stream of conscience" did not flesh out the characters for me. While I don;t expect characters to have modern attitude, I want to be able to understand the character's feelings and emotions. I could not connect the dots. Was Griet projecting the a crush she had on Vermeer onto Pieter? Did she feel nothing for Pieter, but only saw him as a way of escape from the Vermeer household? Or did she finally become attracted to the humanity she eventually saw in Pieter? Or . . . ? We never really find out what she is feeling and what her motivations were. With every man she met younger than 60 making moves on her, she likely could have found other fish in the sea besides Pieter if she was not attracted to him. (The dirty nails and apron??) I'm sensing I have the same dissppointment as the reviewer -- we don't know what the voices and the mannerisms of 300+ years ago were, but we do identify with universal human feelings -- they just need to be communicated a bit more clearly -- many things in this novel made no sense and would be helped by a beam of light here and there aimed toward where we needed to go.]]></body>
  
